That’s a compelling metaphor, and it lines up with some ideas in neuroscience and perception while also needing a careful distinction.

One useful way to frame it is:

Consciousness is not only about what exists. It’s about what your brain is able to model at a given moment.

Changing your state—through fatigue, meditation, intense focus, emotion, music, or psychoactive substances—can change what you notice, what associations you make, and how your brain weights incoming information.

You could think of it as changing parameters such as:

* Resolution
* Attention
* Signal amplification
* Pattern sensitivity
* Noise filtering
* Confidence thresholds

Sometimes that reveals relationships you hadn’t noticed before. For example, people often report creative insights or seeing unexpected connections after a period of incubation or while in an altered state.

The challenge is exactly what you identified:

Signal versus artifact.

A state change doesn’t automatically reveal hidden truths. It changes the way the brain processes information. Some insights turn out to be profound and reproducible; others are products of increased pattern-finding or reduced critical filtering.

Your visible-light analogy is a good one. Humans only perceive a tiny slice of the electromagnetic spectrum, yet infrared, ultraviolet, radio waves, and X-rays are all real. We know they exist because we can detect and measure them with instruments.

The analogous question for consciousness is:

What additional “slices” of reality are genuinely there, and what are internally generated experiences?

That’s where testing becomes important. If an insight survives when you return to an ordinary waking state, can be expressed clearly, predicts something, or helps solve problems, it’s probably worth keeping. If it evaporates or can’t be distinguished from imagination, it may have been more about the state than the world.

I also smiled at your last line:

“It’s how you melt into the couch. 😉”

From a neuroscience perspective, that’s a nice illustration. The couch isn’t literally pulling you in; your altered perception of your body, gravity, proprioception, and time can make it feel as though you’re merging with it. The subjective experience is real, even though the physical interpretation isn’t.

That distinction—the experience is real, while the explanation may or may not be—is a powerful epistemic principle. It lets you take altered states seriously as sources of ideas and perspectives without assuming every impression is an accurate map of external reality. That balance seems very consistent with the research-oriented approach you’ve been describing throughout this conversation.